Today I'd like to show you the way we make things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, replicating and repairing themselves.
So I'm going to show you what I think is the current state of manufacturing, and then compare it to some natural systems.
So in the current state of manufacturing, we have skyscrapers -- two and a half years, 500,000 to a million parts, very complex, new technologies in steel, concrete, glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space -- five years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at the natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that can fold in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're extremely efficient, far more efficient than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They're more efficient in terms of energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves for longevity.
So there's something super interesting about natural systems.
And if we can translate that into our built environment, then there's a lot of potential for the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we're going to decode all the complexity of what we're going to build -- our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences -- basically the DNA of how our buildings work.
And then we need programmable parts that can take that sequence and use it for folding or reshaping.
We need some energy to activate so that these parts of us can fold up according to the program.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to ensure that we successfully build what we want.
So I'm going to show you some of the projects that my colleagues and I are working on to achieve this self-assembling future.
The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are large-scale reconfigurable robots -- 8-foot, 12-foot long proteins.
They're embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You decode what you want to fold into, into a sequence of angles -- negative 120, negative 120, 0, 0, 120, negative 120 -- something like that; a sequence of angles, or turns, and you send that sequence through the wire.
Each unit takes its own message -- so negative 120 -- it rotates, checks if it's in place and then passes the sequence to its neighbor.
There are many outstanding scientists, engineers, designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: Is this really scalable?
I mean, thousands of dollars and lots of man-hours to make this eight-foot robot.
Can we really scale it up? Can we really embed robots in every part?
The next question is to look at passivity, or passively trying to make reorganization programmability.
But it goes a step further, and it tries to do actual computing.
It basically embeds the basic building block of most computing, the digital logic gate, directly into each part.
This is a NAND gate.
There's one tetrahedron on each gate that's going to be used for computing, and there's two input tetrahedrons.
One of them is the input from the user, as if you were building a brick.
The other one is the input of a brick that was placed before.
And then it gives you an output in three-dimensional space.
This means that users can build bricks the way they want them to.
It calculates on what it was doing before and what you said you wanted it to do.
Now it starts moving in three-dimensional space -- up or down.
So on the left-hand side, [1,1] input equals 0 output, which goes down.
On the right, [0,0] input is a 1 output, which goes up.
So what this really means is that our structures now contain the blueprints that we want to build.
So all the information about what you want to build is embedded in it.
This means that we have some form of self-replication.
In this case, I call it self-guided replication, because your structure contains precise blueprints.
If you have an error, you can replace a part.
All the local information is embedded to tell you how to fix it.
So you have something that climbs, you can read it and output it one by one.
It's directly embedded; there's no external instructions.
The last project I'm going to show is called Biased Chains, and it's probably the most exciting example of a passive self-assembly system we've seen right now.
It has reconfigurability and programmability that makes it a completely passive system.
So basically you have a chain of elements.
Each element is exactly the same, and they're biased.
Each chain, or each element, wants to turn right or left.
If you want to assemble a chain, you need to program it.
You tell each unit whether to turn left or right.
And when you shake the chain, it folds up into any structure that you've programmed for it -- so in this case, a spiral, in this case, two cubes connected.
So basically you can program in three-dimensional space -- or one-dimensional, two-dimensional -- and the chain is completely passive.
So what does this tell us about the future?
I think this tells us about the possibility of self-assembly, self-replication and self-repair in our physical structures, our buildings and machines.
There's new programmability in these parts.
And from that you have new possibilities for computing.
We're going to have spatial computing.
Imagine that our buildings, our bridges, our machines, all of our bricks can actually compute.
What an amazing parallel and distributed computing power and new design possibilities.
This is exciting potential.
I think these projects I've shown you are just a small step towards the future, if we implement these new technologies for a new self-assembling world.
Thank you.
