Recently, we've seen the effects of cyber attacks on the business world.
Data breaches at companies like JPMorgan Chase, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target have caused losses of hundreds of millions, if not billions, of dollars.
A few more attacks like this, and the entire world economy will collapse.
The public sector has not been immune.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a very serious data breach at the US Office of Personnel Management.
Security clearance and fingerprint information was stolen, affecting 22 million employees.
And you may have heard that some government-sponsored hackers are trying to use stolen data to influence election outcomes in some countries.
Two recent examples are the theft of large-scale data from the German Bundestag and the theft of emails from the US Democratic National Committee.
The cyber threat is already affecting our democratic processes.
And it's likely to get worse.
The more advanced computer technology is, the more vulnerable the means we use to protect our data.
In particular, a new type of computer technology, called quantum computing, uses microscopic particles in nature to dramatically increase the computational power of computers.
It's powerful enough to crack many of the encryption systems we use today.
So are we hopeless?
Should we start packing our electronic survival gear for the upcoming data apocalypse?
I think, not yet.
Quantum computers are still in the labs, and it will take years for them to be put to practical use.
More important, there have been major breakthroughs in the field of encryption.
For me, this is a very exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned that we had unlocked new skills to create quantum effects that don't exist in nature, I was excited.
The idea of using the fundamental laws of physics to advance encryption excites me.
Today, a select group of companies and labs, including mine, are taking this technology to practical applications.
That's right.
We're going to fight quantum with quantum.
How does this work?
First, let's take a quick look at the world of encryption.
You need a briefcase, you have some important documents to send to your friend, James Bond, and you need to lock it up for safety.
Because these materials are top secret, we're going to use a super-advanced briefcase.
It comes with a special combination lock that, once locked, converts the contents of the document to random numbers.
So you just put the documents in, close the lock, and by this time the documents have been converted to random numbers, and you send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on its way, you call him to give him the code.
As soon as he gets the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are unscrambled, and you successfully send an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A fun example, but it does illustrate three things important for encryption.
The code -- we call this an encryption key.
You can think of it as a code.
The call to James to give him the code.
We call this key exchange.
This ensures that we can safely deliver the keys to the right place.
And the lock used to encrypt and decrypt the documents.
We call this an encryption algorithm.
Using the key, it converts the contents of the document to random numbers.
A good algorithm can do this, and it's hard to break the code without the key.
The importance of the algorithm is that if someone gets the briefcase and opens it, without the key and without knowing the encryption algorithm, they can't read the document.
All you get is a bunch of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure method of key exchange to communicate the key to the right place.
However, rapid increases in computing power are putting at risk many of the key exchange methods we currently use.
For example, we now have a very widely used system -- RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it took about 40 billion years to break a 426-bit RSA key.
And in 1994, just 17 years later, the code was broken.
As computers have become more and more powerful, we've had to use larger and larger codes.
Now we often use 2048 or 4096 bits.
As you can see, the battle between the encryptors and the breakers is going on, trying to defeat each other.
And when quantum computers arrive in the next 10 to 15 years, they will even more rapidly crack the complex mathematical algorithms that underlie the encryption systems we use today.
In fact, quantum computers will turn our security castle into a mere house of cards.
We have to find a way to protect our castle.
There's been a growing body of research in recent years looking at how quantum effects can be used to enhance encryption.
There have been some exciting breakthroughs.
Remember the three things important for encryption -- high-quality keys, secure key exchange and a strong algorithm.
However, advances in science and engineering have put two of these priorities at risk.
First of all, the keys.
Random numbers are the building blocks of encryption keys.
But today, they're not truly random.
For example, we generate keys based on the frequency of random numbers, generated by software, which we call pseudo-random numbers.
Numbers generated by a program or a mathematical method will always have some, perhaps less obvious, pattern in them.
The less random the numbers are, or in technical terms, the less entropy they contain, the easier they are to predict.
Recently, some casinos have been attacked in a creative way.
They took pictures of the slot machines for a period of time and then analyzed them.
The cyber criminals used reverse engineering to create the pseudo-random number generator behind the turntable.
So they have a good chance of predicting the spins of the wheels and making a lot of money.
The keys are equally insecure.
Having a true random number generator is important for generating secure passwords.
For years, researchers have been working on building true random number generators.
But most designs are either not random enough, fast enough, or difficult to reuse.
But the quantum world is truly random.
It's important to take advantage of this true randomness.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can produce a continuous stream of random numbers very quickly.
The casino crime that I was talking about is no longer possible.
Several universities and companies around the world are focusing on building true random number generators.
At my company, our quantum random number generator was born out of a two meter by one meter optical table.
And then we reduced it to the size of a box.
Today, it's possible to put it on a PCI card and plug it into an ordinary computer.
This is the world's fastest, truly random number generator.
It measures quantum effects to produce a billion random numbers per second.
Today it has been widely used around the world to improve the security of cloud providers, banks and government agencies.
(Applause) But even with a true random number generator, we still face the second big cyber threat: The problem of secure key exchange.
Current key exchange technology will not stand up to a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called quantum key distribution, or QKD, which takes advantage of a fundamental, counterintuitive characteristic of quantum mechanics.
The act of looking at a microscopic particle changes that particle.
Let me give you an example.
Consider again, we're going to give the code to James Bond.
But this time, instead of calling him, we're going to use quantum effects to carry the code on a laser and send it to James via standard optical fiber.
We assume that Dr. No wants to get the code.
Fortunately, Dr. No's attempt to intercept this quantum key will leave an electronic fingerprint that James and you can detect.
This allows the intercepted key to be discarded.
And the keys that are left behind can provide strong data protection.
Because this security mechanism is based on the fundamental principles of physics, a quantum computer, or any future supercomputer, will not be able to crack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities and the defense sector to improve this exciting technology and develop the next generation of security products.
The Internet of Things heralds a highly interconnected era, with 25 to 30 billion devices expected to be connected to the Internet by 2020.
For our societies to function properly in an IoT world, trust in these interconnected device systems is essential.
We believe that quantum technology will be very important in building this trust, enabling us to fully benefit from these amazing innovations that can enrich our lives.
Thank you.
