You all know the truth of what I'm going to say.
I think the intuition that inequality can cause social fragmentation and corruption has been around since before the French Revolution.
The difference is that we can now find evidence that we can compare societies, societies with different levels of equality, to understand the effects of inequality.
I'm going to show you some data and explain why that data is actually related.
But first, let's see how miserable our lives are.
(Laughter) I'd like to start my speech with a paradox.
This shows you life expectancy in relation to gross national income -- how rich countries are on average.
You see the countries on the right, like Norway and the United States, are twice as rich as Israel, Greece, Portugal on the left.
But that doesn't affect their life expectancy.
There's no suggestion of a relationship.
But if we look within our societies, we can see that there are huge differences in health within their entire societies.
This is still life expectancy.
These are small towns in England and Wales -- the poorest on the right, the richest on the left.
There's a big difference between the poor and the rest of us.
Even the people just below the top have poorer health than the people at the top.
So income means a lot in our societies, but it doesn't make sense in comparison between societies.
The explanation of that paradox is that, in our societies, we're looking at relative income or social status, social status -- where we are in relation to each other and the size of the differences between us.
As soon as you have that idea, you should immediately wonder: What happens if the gap widens, what if it narrows, widens or narrows the income gap?
That's what I'm going to tell you.
I'm not using any hypothetical data.
My data comes from the United Nations -- like the World Bank -- on the income differences between these rich, developed market democracies.
The method we use, simple and easy to understand, and you can download it, is to compare the income differences between the top 20 percent and the bottom 20 percent in each country.
You can see that the countries on the left are more equal -- Japan, Finland, Norway, Sweden -- and the top 20 percent are about 3.5 to 4 times as rich as the bottom 20 percent.
But on the more unequal end -- U.K., Portugal, USA, Singapore -- the income differences are twice as large.
In this way, our country (the UK) is twice as unequal as some of the other successful democratic markets.
Now I'm going to show you what that does to our societies.
We collected data on problems with social gradients, which are more common at the bottom of the social ladder.
Internationally comparable data include life expectancy, children's maths and literacy scores, infant mortality rates, suicide rates, proportion of the population in prison, teenage pregnancy rates, levels of trust, obesity, mental illness -- which in standard diagnostic classification includes drug and alcohol addiction -- and social mobility.
We put all of this into one coefficient.
They're all weighted equally.
A country's score is the average of these factors.
As you can see, these scores are related to the inequality comparison I've just shown you, and I'm going to show that data over and over again.
The more unequal countries do worse on all kinds of social problems.
There's a very strong correlation.
But if you look at the same index of health and social problems in relation to gross national income per capita and gross national income, there's nothing there, no correlation anymore.
We were a little bit worried that people might think that we were choosing specific problems to suit our theories and then artificially creating evidence, so we also published a paper in the British Medical Journal on the UNICEF index of child well-being.
It has 40 different parts, summed up by others.
It includes whether children can talk to their parents, whether they have books at home, what immunization rates are, and whether there's bullying at school.
Everything goes into it.
So that's how the index relates to the same level of inequality.
Children do worse in the more unequal societies.
Highly significant relationship.
But again, if you look at the relationship between child well-being and national income per capita, you're going to get nowhere. There's no suggestion of a relationship.
All the data I've shown you so far reveals the same thing.
The average well-being of our societies is no longer dependent on national income and economic growth.
They're very important in poorer countries, but not in the rich developed world.
And the differences between us and where we are in relation to each other now seem very important.
Now I'm going to show you some of the parts of our index.
This is the mutual trust index.
It's the proportion of the population who agree that most people can be trusted.
This is data from the World Values Survey.
You see, on the more unequal side, about 15 percent of the population feel they can trust others.
But in the more equal societies, it rises to 60 or 65 percent.
If you look at measures of participation in community activities or social capital, there are very similar relationships closely related to inequality.
I would say, we did this work twice.
We did it first on these rich developed countries, and then we changed the test and repeated it on the 50 American states -- asking the same question: Do the more unequal states do worse on all of these measures?
This is the relationship between trust and inequality in a general social survey conducted by the federal government.
Very similar scatter over a similar range of levels of trust.
The same thing is going on.
Basically we found that almost all of the factors related to trust that are reflected in international surveys are also reflected in the 50 states that we surveyed separately.
This is no coincidence.
This is mental illness.
The World Health Organization collects data using the same diagnostic interviews on random samples that allow us to compare rates of mental illness in each society.
This is the proportion of the population with any mental illness in the previous year.
It goes from about 8 percent to more than 24 percent -- which means that society as a whole is three times as likely to have mental illness as any other society.
